 in Shanghai, and some showed the tastes of the tenants.</div><div><br></div><div>When we were first invited to the Creation of Creators design show (a new platform at the 2018 Maison Shanghai home decor trade show), we were honestly a bit confused — Why would they invite us? In 2016 and 2017, we worked on many projects, but they seemingly had little to do with design. Through conversations with the design show’s sponsor Zhou Chenchen, we gained an understanding of the show’s intention. We thought, maybe we could do something that we were actually interested in.</div><div><br></div><div>We are a team based in Xiamen, but since many of our projects took place in Shanghai, I was searching for an apartment in Shanghai. As I was doing some searching on an intermediary website for real estates, I discovered that the rental rates have changed a lot since 10 years ago, when I was still living in Shanghai. I found some apartments under 8000 RMB on lianjia.com (an intermediary website), many of them were 1-room apartments that are common in Shanghai, and some showed the tastes of the tenants.</div><div><br></div><div><br></div>',NULL,'2020-05-31 00:00:00','1','Artist Talk','6:30 pm EST',_binary 'Lin Aojie was born in Guangzhou in 1986 and graduated from Guangzhou Academy of Fine Arts, Oil Painting Department in 2010. He currently lives and works in Guangzhou.<br><br>Presented through video, photography, painting, text, etc., Lin Aojie’s artistic practice departs from his personal experiences. The artist has a keen and delicate record of the trivial details of daily life or deliberately planned events with strongly improvisatory and humorous images, while a seemingly dispassionate tone threads the whole narrative structure. By beating around the bush he tries to question, ridicule and criticize the capitalist mode of production, artist’s survival predicament and the relationship between artists and other art professionals.&nbsp;a keen and delicate record of the trivial detail